description.narrative: By 2022 Government and partners are able to plan and implement the delivery of equitable, gender responsive, and quality hygiene and safe sanitation services at scale, for households in the most vulnerable and deprived communities., which contributes to Sanitation, Sanitation (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Infants, young children, and caregivers especially the most vulnerable have equitable access to and use sustainable, safe, and affordable Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH) services (including in Institutions) across the lifecycle.

description.narrative: 2019 was a critical year to ensure that Clean India Mission (SBM) continues beyond its programmed end in October 2019. UNICEF (1) updated the 10 year rural sanitation strategy, (2) developed content of the ODF-Sustainability and ODF (FSM, SLWM) programmes, generated robust evidence which was used by the sector to request a further budgetary allocation of $ 12.5 billion for rural sanitation by 2024, fostered strategic partnership and led a large scale capacity development campaign to reach all 250,000 GPs of India. Over 18 million people received access to Household toilets for the first time in UNICEF supported districts. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:06/02/2020
